  <title>Forces</title>
  <keywords>
    <keyword>Forces</keyword>
    <keyword>Kinetostatic-Forces</keyword>
  </keywords>
  <body>
    <para styleclass="Normal"><table styleclass="PopupTable" rowcount="1" colcount="1">
      <tr style="vertical-align:top">
        <td>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box"><text styleclass="VariableName-small">Kinetostatic Forces</text> are those forces and reaction forces in parts and at joints that are a consequence of their movement.</para>
          <para styleclass="Popup Box">We tend to use the terms:</para>
          <list id="0" type="ul" listtype="bullet" formatstring="&#183;" format-charset="SYMBOL_CHARSET" levelreset="true" legalstyle="false" startfrom="1" styleclass="Popup Box" style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:8pt; color:#000000;">
            <li styleclass="Popup Box"><text styleclass="VariableName-small">Drive Torque</text> (also called the <text styleclass="VariableName-small">Application-Load</text>) for the <text styleclass="VariableName-small">moment</text> a Rotary Motor must provide to the kinematic-chain.</li>
            <li styleclass="Popup Box"><text styleclass="VariableName-small">Drive Force</text> for the <text styleclass="VariableName-small">linear force</text> a <text styleclass="VariableName-small">Linear Motor</text> must provide to the kinematic-chain.</li>
          </list>
        </td>
      </tr>
    </table></para>
  </body>
</topic>
